blished by the US Census Bureau, the Spanish or Italian preposition with fused definite article <i>del</i> ‘of the’, which forms first part of surnames such as   Del Cid   and   Del Signore  , has apparently been in some instances counted as an independent surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Delle","meanings":["German: habitational name from a place so named in North Rhine-Westphalia or a topographic name (see   Dell  ).","French (Lorraine): habitational name from Delle, a place in Territoire de Belfort. Alternatively, a topographic name, with fused preposition <i>d(e)</i> ‘from’, for someone who lived near a prominent alder tree or trees, from <i>elle</i>, a derivative of Middle High German <i>erle</i> ‘alder’."]}]},{"name":"Bosco","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Salvatore, Carmine, Sal, Ignazio, Antonio, Attilio, Cosimo, Francesco, Gaspare, Luigi, Saverio.","Italian: topographic name for someone living or working in a wood, from <i>bosco</i> ‘wood’, from Late Latin <i>boscus</i> ‘shrub, undergrowth’ (of Gallic or ancient Germanic origin), or a habitational name from a place called with this word. In some cases it may have been an occupational name for a woodsman or forester and, by extension, a nickname for a surly or rough person. Compare   Lo Bosco  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Boschetti","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Mario, Angelina, Antonio, Guido, Rosario.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of a diminutive of   Bosco  ."]},{"name":"Lo Bosco","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Carmine, Gennaro, Sal, Salvatore, Antonino, Nichola, Pasquale, Piera, Raffaela, Rocco.","Italian (southern; also <b>Lobosco</b>): variant of   Bosco  , with the addition of the definite article <i>lo</i>."]}]},{"name":"Helena","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 200